---
import ArticleLayout from "../../components/ArticleLayout.astro";

const title = "Energy: Fusion, Storage, and the Smarter Grid — Future";
const updated = "Updated: 2026";
---

<ArticleLayout title={title}>
  <article class="page">
    <header class="hero">
      <div class="hero-top">
        <a class="back" href="/">← Back to Atlas</a>
        <span class="chip chip--topic">ENERGY</span>
      </div>

      <h1>Energy: Fusion, Storage, and the Smarter Grid</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">Even before fusion arrives, batteries + software can reshape the grid — balancing supply and demand in real time.</p>

      <div class="hero-grid">
        <section class="card card--soft">
          <h2 class="hsmall">What you’ll learn</h2>
          <ul class="list">
            <li>Why storage matters even without fusion.</li>
            <li>How software turns many small sources into one reliable system.</li>
            <li>What to watch: cost curves, permitting, and transmission.</li>
          </ul>
        </section>

        <section class="card card--ink">
          <p class="quote">“The future grid is part power plant, part computer.”</p>
          <p class="meta">{updated}</p>
        </section>
      </div>
    </header>

    <section class="section">
      <h2>TL;DR</h2>
      <div class="tldr">
        <div class="tldr-item">
          <div class="dot dot--a" aria-hidden="true"></div>
          <div>
            <h3>Storage is the workhorse</h3>
            <p>Batteries, pumped hydro, and demand response stabilize renewables.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="tldr-item">
          <div class="dot dot--b" aria-hidden="true"></div>
          <div>
            <h3>Grid intelligence scales</h3>
            <p>Forecasting and control software reduces waste and blackouts.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="tldr-item">
          <div class="dot dot--c" aria-hidden="true"></div>
          <div>
            <h3>Fusion is a high-uncertainty bonus</h3>
            <p>If it works economically, it changes everything — but timelines are uncertain.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <h2>The boring revolution: storage + control</h2>
      <p class="lead">Most grid wins come from better storage, better forecasting, and faster control loops — not sci-fi reactors.</p>
      <div class="card"><div class="grid3">
          <div class="mini"><h4>Batteries</h4><p>Fast response, improving costs, good for minutes-to-hours balancing.</p></div>
          <div class="mini"><h4>Demand response</h4><p>Pay devices and buildings to shift usage when the grid is stressed.</p></div>
          <div class="mini"><h4>Transmission</h4><p>Move power from where it's produced to where it's needed — often the bottleneck.</p></div>
        </div></div>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <h2>Fusion: what it would take</h2>
      <p class="lead">Fusion needs to be not only possible, but <b>reliable</b>, <b>maintainable</b>, and <b>cheaper than alternatives</b>.</p>
      <div class="two-col">
        <div class="card"><h3 class="hsmall">Engineering hurdles</h3>
          <ul class="list">
            <li>Containing plasma reliably and continuously.</li>
            <li>Materials that survive heat + neutron damage.</li>
            <li>Maintenance cycles that don't kill economics.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="card"><h3 class="hsmall">Economic hurdles</h3>
          <ul class="list">
            <li>Capital costs vs solar/wind + storage.</li>
            <li>Regulation, permitting, and supply chain scale.</li>
            <li>Proving uptime over years, not minutes.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
      <p class="note">Fusion is real physics. The question is industrial reality.</p>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <h2>FAQ</h2>
      <div class="faq">
        <details><summary>Is fusion always 30 years away?</summary><p>It's a joke because timelines slip. Progress is real, but commercial proof requires long uptime and low cost.</p></details>
        <details><summary>What's the sure bet?</summary><p>Better grids: storage, transmission, and software efficiency improvements.</p></details>
      </div>
    </section>

    <nav class="footnav" aria-label="Next and previous">
      <a class="btn btn--ghost" href="/future/space-economy">← Prev: Space</a>
      <a class="btn" href="/future/quantum-post-crypto">Next: Quantum →</a>
    </nav>
  </article>

</ArticleLayout>
